\f0\b \cf0 Decision rationale:
\f1\b0 \
There were three main reasons for opting for GitHub Actions over the others:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Zero infrastructure overhead.
\f1\b0  No overhead of infrastructure. Jenkins needs a server to be set up and managed. Using App Runner and Render for this project was specifically intended to avoid doing so. Opting for Jenkins would defeat this very purpose.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Native GitHub integration.
\f1\b0  This repository exists on GitHub and GitHub Actions has an inbuilt compatibility with pull requests, branch protections, the GitHub Environments functionality (which even mandates explicit approval before production deployment) without having to do anything extra.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
AWS ecosystem support.
\f1\b0   The github.com/aws-actions repository at the GitHub Marketplace offers officially supported actions for things like Amazon EC2 RDP login (amazon-ecr-login), configuration of credentials (configure-aws-credentials) and many more. They've been tested thoroughly by the AWS team and will be kept up to date.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 CircleCI would have been a strong secondary option since its YAML file format is almost identical to that of GitHub Actions and has a good free plan. But then again, CircleCI would mandate having another account setup with GitHub OAuth integration.\cf4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

